  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Meyer's NT Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Timothy 3:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Matthies (with whom Wiesinger agrees) thus states the connection between this and the preceding verses: “Quite different is it with evil men, who, instead of suffering for the truth, proceed always farther in their wickedness;” but there is no real opposition in the two thoughts thus opposed.[52] The apostle here continues the description of the heretics which was interrupted at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Timothy 3:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; in contrast with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "οἱ θέλοντες εὐσεβῶς ζῆν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", he calls them ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πονηροὶ ἄνθρωποι καὶ γόητες",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and says of them, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "προκόπτειν ἐπὶ τὸ χεῖρον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which is all the more suitable that it was the very reason why persecution was threatening the honest disciples of Christ, and with them Timothy.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πονηροὶ δὲ ἄνθρωποι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] As the article is wanting, the thought is quite general, but ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "καὶ γόητες",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " clearly shows that the heretics mentioned above are specially meant (in opposition to Hofmann). Paul gives this name to the heretics, with reference to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Timothy 3:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where he compared them to the Egyptian ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "sorcerers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "γόης",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἅπ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "λεγ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "γοητεία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Ma 12:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); it is equivalent to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "μάγος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 13:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 13:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (comp., too, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 8:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 8:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Hofmann generalizes the idea to that of a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "traitor",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; but this is all the more arbitrary, that the expression is undoubtedly an allusion to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Timothy 3:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "προκόψουσιν ἐπὶ τὸ χεῖρον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] denotes a greater degree of wickedness, while ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Timothy 3:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " refers to the increase in the extent of its influence.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "How this increase of wickedness comes to pass, is told by the words ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πλανῶντες καὶ πλανώμενοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Bengel and Heydenreich make ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πλανῶντες",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "γόητες",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πλανώμενοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πονηροί",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " parallel to each other; for this, however, there is no ground. Even the meaning of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πλανώμενοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is against the parallel, for it is neither transitive: “leading astray” (Matthies), nor middle: qui se seducendos permittunt (Bengel), nor even intransitive: “going astray” (Hofmann); it is purely passive: “being led astray” (Luther), or otherwise it would have been put first. He who leads others astray is himself led astray.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
