  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "But evil men and seducers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The word ‘seduce’ in A.V. occurs nine times in Old and New Testament always in the general sense of ‘lead astray’; everywhere except here it is used to represent the Greek word for this cognate to the English word ‘planet’ ‘the wanderer,’ (cf. Jude’s ‘wandering stars’) and almost immediately following here ‘deceiving,’ cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Timothy 4:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and note. R.V. in these places varies between ‘seduce’ and ‘lead astray.’ The word so rendered here is properly ‘enchanter,’ from the cries of incantations used. So ‘magicians,’ and more generally ‘impostors.’ Compare for the general sense, the most probable here, the use of the verb by Plato, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Phæd",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". 81, 13, ‘the soul having served and loved the body and been ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "bewitched",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " by it through desires and pleasures.’ Some think there may be a reference to the magic arts, such as those of Jannes and Jambres; and certainly Ephesus had an evil repute in this respect itself, cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 19:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 19:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ‘Ephesian letters’ was a common expression for charms made up of magic words and worn as amulets.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "shall wax worse and worse",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The same verb as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Timothy 3:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The ‘progress’ is a ‘rake’s progress,’ step after step ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "leading and being led astray",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Compare ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 18:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ‘with thy sorcery were all the nations ",
        "children": []
      },
